{
  "texts": [
    "Intuitively, TracInRP maps gradient vectors into a d-dimensional subspace (d ≪ p) via multiplication by a d × p random matrix where each entry is sampled i.i.d.",
    "from Gaussian distribution N 0, 1 d.",
    "These low-memory gradient \"sketches\" are used in place of the full gradient vectors in Eq.",
    "(55) (Woodruff, 2014).",
    "TracInRP is primarily targeted at applications where p is sufficiently large that storing the full training set's gradient vectors (∀ t,i ∇ L(z i; (t-1))) is prohibitive."
  ]
}